Base.Explanation:
Create a user account in Active Directory. The account is created in a Active Directory domain, organizational unit or other container. Optionally, you can specify the domain controller on which the user creation is created.
With this action you can not create local user accounts on non domain controllers or computer running Windows NT4.

ArrayElement.Name: Domain
ArrayElement.Description: The name of the domain (DNS or NETBIOS style, e.g. tools4ever.com or TOOLS4EVER) where the account will be created. Optionally you can specify the property 'Organizational Unit-Container'. If you specify a value for this property, do not specify a value for property 'LDAP-container' since this specification takes precedence.

ArrayElement.Name: Organizational Unit-Container
ArrayElement.Description: The name of the Organizational Unit-Container where the user account must be created (example: Students or Students\Group1). If you specify a value for this property, you should also specify a value for the 'Domain' property. If you specify a value for this property, do not specify a value for property 'LDAP-container' since that specification overrules this specification.

ArrayElement.Name: LDAP Container
ArrayElement.Description: The LDAP name of the organizational unit or container where the user account must be created (example: cn=Users, cn=Tools4ever, cn=Com). You must specify either a value for this property or values for the properties 'Domain' and 'Organizational Unit-Container'. If values for both methods are specified, this method takes precedence.

ArrayElement.Name: Domain (controller)
ArrayElement.Description: Optional: The name of the domain controller or domain, used to access to the domain, container or organizational unit where the account must be created. If this value is not specified or the name of a domain is specified, the application creates the account on a domain controller that is to be determined by Active Directory (serverless binding). If a domain controller is specified, the account is explicitly created on the specified controller (server binding). In both cases, Active Directory will replicate the account information to all domain controllers in the Active Directory forests and domains.

ArrayElement.Name: Name generation algorithm
ArrayElement.Description: The algorithm used to generate the username and full name of the user account. In general the variables %FirstName%, %MiddleName% and %LastName% are used to generate values for the variables %UserName% and %FullName% which are assigned to various name attributes.

ArrayElement.Name: SAM-Account-Name
ArrayElement.Description: The user logon name (pre-Windows 2000) without the (NETBIOS) domain name. In most cases the SAM-Account-Name is equal to the prefix of the User-Principal-Name and specified by the general user name variable. The name must be unique within the domain.

ArrayElement.Name: User-Principal-Name
ArrayElement.Description: The User-Principal-Name (UPN) is an Internet-style login name for the user. The UPN is the preferred logon name for Active Directory users. Users should be using their UPNs to log on to the domain. The UPN has the format 'account_name@domain.com', where 'account_name' is the upn-prefix and 'domain.com' is the upn-suffix. In most cases the User-Principal-Name prefix is specified by the general user name variable.

ArrayElement.Name: CommonName
ArrayElement.Description: The 'CommonName' corresponds with the full name of the user account. This name is most common used in Windows' user interfaces when showing names.

ArrayElement.Name: DisplayName
ArrayElement.Description: The 'DisplayName' in most cases corresponds with the full name of the user account.

ArrayElement.Name: Given-name
ArrayElement.Description: The Given-name corresponds with the first name of the user account. The Given-name is an optional attribute of Active Directory user accounts.

ArrayElement.Name: Initials
ArrayElement.Description: The 'Initials'-field name corresponds with the middle name of the user account. The 'Initials'-field is an optional attribute of Active Directory user accounts.

ArrayElement.Name: Surname
ArrayElement.Description: The 'Surname' corresponds with the last name of the user account. The 'Surname' is an optional attribute of Active Directory user accounts.

ArrayElement.Name: Password generator
ArrayElement.Description: A password can be generated automatically. The 'Password generator' specifies how the password is generated, e.g. password length, password complexity requirements, password output variable etc. When this property is specified the password is generated automatically. The password output variable (default: %Password%) should correspond with the variable generated by the password generator.

ArrayElement.Name: Password
ArrayElement.Description: The password of the user account.

ArrayElement.Name: Description
ArrayElement.Description: A user comment. The field can contain a text of any length.

ArrayElement.Name: Home directory
ArrayElement.Description: The path of the home directory of the user account. Note that the home directory is not created because of this specification. Instead, it specifies the home directory in the Active Directory. You can create the home directory, by adding the action 'Create Directory' to the script.

ArrayElement.Name: Home directory drive
ArrayElement.Description: The drive letter assigned to the user's home directory for logon purposes. The drive letter must be specified as <driver-letter>:, for example E: or F:.

ArrayElement.Name: User profile
ArrayElement.Description: A path to the user's profile. Note that this specification does not create the profile directory. Instead, it specifies the profile's path in the SAM user account database. You can create the profile directory, by adding the action 'Create Directory' to the script.

ArrayElement.Name: Logon script
ArrayElement.Description: The path for the user's logon script file. The script file can be a .CMD file, an .EXE file, or a .BAT file.

ArrayElement.Name: User must change password at next logon
ArrayElement.Description: The password is expired. Default value: 'Yes' (password has been expired). Use this property to force the user to change the password at the next logon. Note that the user can logon using the current password.

ArrayElement.Name: User cannot change password
ArrayElement.Description: The user cannot change password. Default value: 'No' (user can change password). When the user cannot change the password, only the administrator can change the password.

ArrayElement.Name: Password never expires
ArrayElement.Description: The password should never expire on the account. Default value: 'No' (password does expire).

ArrayElement.Name: Store password using reversible encryption
ArrayElement.Description: An password specific option. If you have users logging on to your Windows 2000 network from Apple computers, select this option for those user accounts.

ArrayElement.Name: Account disabled
ArrayElement.Description: The user's account is disabled. Default value: 'No'. If a user account is disabled, the account does exist but cannot be used to logon to the network.

ArrayElement.Name: Smart card is required for interactive logon
ArrayElement.Description: Default value: 'No'. Specify 'Yes' to securely store public and private keys, passwords, and other types of personal information for this user account. There must be a smart card reader attached to the user's computer, and they must have a personal identification number (PIN) to be able to log on to the network.

ArrayElement.Name: Account is trusted for delegation
ArrayElement.Description: Default value: 'No'. Specify 'Yes' to give a user the ability to assign responsibility for management and administration of a portion of the domain namespace to another user, group, or organization.

ArrayElement.Name: Account is sensitive and cannot be delegated
ArrayElement.Description: Default value: 'No'. Specify 'Yes' if this account cannot be assigned for delegation by another account.

ArrayElement.Name: Use DES encryption types for this account
ArrayElement.Description: Default value: 'No'. Specify 'Yes' if if you need the Data Encryption Standard (DES). DES supports multiple levels of encryption, including MPPE Standard (40-bit), MPPE Standard (56-bit), MPPE Strong (128-bit), IPSec DES (40-bit), IPSec 56-bit DES, and IPSec Triple DES (3DES). For more information on any of these encryption types, see Windows 2000 Help.

ArrayElement.Name: Don't require Kerberos preauthentication
ArrayElement.Description: Default value: 'No'. Specify 'Yes' if the account uses another implementation of the Kerberos protocol. Not all implementations or deployments of the Kerberos protocol use this feature. The Kerberos Key Distribution Center uses ticket-granting tickets for obtaining network authentication in a domain. The time at which the Key Distribution Center issues a ticket-granting ticket is important to the Kerberos protocol. Windows 2000 uses other mechanisms to synchronize time, so using the Kerberos preauthentication option works well.

ArrayElement.Name: Computer account
ArrayElement.Description: This is a computer account for a MS Windows NT Workstation/Windows 2000 Professional or Windows NT Server/Windows 2000 Server that is a member of this domain. Default value: 'No'.

ArrayElement.Name: Account expiration
ArrayElement.Description: The time and date when the account expires. The value can be 'Never' or a time and date.

ArrayElement.Name: Logon hours
ArrayElement.Description: The hours the user account can log on to the domain. By default, domain logon is allowed 24 hours a day, 7 days a week.

ArrayElement.Name: Workstations
ArrayElement.Description: Optional: the names of the workstations from which the user can log on (8 maximum), separated by commas.

ArrayElement.Name: General - Office
ArrayElement.Description: This is the person's office location, including the building and office address or number.

ArrayElement.Name: General - Telephone number
ArrayElement.Description: The person's phone number.

ArrayElement.Name: General - E-mail
ArrayElement.Description: The person's e-mail address. The e-mail address appears with the universal principal name suffix (for example, someone@microsoft.com).

ArrayElement.Name: General - Web-page
ArrayElement.Description: The person's home page URL, either on the Internet or in the local intranet site.

ArrayElement.Name: Address - Street
ArrayElement.Description: The person's street address in this space.

ArrayElement.Name: Address - P.O. Box
ArrayElement.Description: The person's Post Office box number in this space.

ArrayElement.Name: Address - City
ArrayElement.Description: The city where this person is located.

ArrayElement.Name: Address - State/province
ArrayElement.Description: The state or province where this person is located.

ArrayElement.Name: Address - Zip/Postal Code
ArrayElement.Description: The zip or postal code applicable for the person.

ArrayElement.Name: Address - Country/region
ArrayElement.Description: This person's country or region

ArrayElement.Name: Telephone number - home
ArrayElement.Description: The home telephone number for this person.

ArrayElement.Name: Telephone number - pager
ArrayElement.Description: The pager number for this person.

ArrayElement.Name: Telephone number - mobile
ArrayElement.Description: The mobile or cellular phone number for this user.

ArrayElement.Name: Telephone number - fax
ArrayElement.Description: The person's fax machine number here.

ArrayElement.Name: Telephone number - IP phone
ArrayElement.Description: This person's IP telephony number.

ArrayElement.Name: Telephone - Notes
ArrayElement.Description: Descriptive information to add any comments for this person.

ArrayElement.Name: Organization - Department
ArrayElement.Description: The department for this person

ArrayElement.Name: Organization - Title
ArrayElement.Description: The title for this person

ArrayElement.Name: Organization - Company
ArrayElement.Description: The company for this person

ArrayElement.Name: User Object Distinguished Name
ArrayElement.Description: The Object Distinguished Name of the new user account. This property is an 'output only' property and is generated by the application automatically. The 'User Object Distinguished Name' is created by the Active Directory automatically when the user account is created. Once the user account is created, you can store the Object Distinguished Name in a variable (%UserODN%) and use the variable in subsequent actions.

ArrayElement.Name: User Security Identifier (SID)
ArrayElement.Description: The security identifier (SID) of the new user account. This property is an 'output only' property and is generated by the application automatically. The 'User Security Identifier' (SID) is created by the Active Directory automatically when the user account is created. The SID is used when setting permissions, for instance on home directories, Exchange mailboxes etc. Once the user account is created, you can store the SID in a variable (%UserSid%) and use this variable to setup permissions.

ArrayElement.Name: User Object
ArrayElement.Description: An internal data structure representing the user account. This property is an 'output only' property and is generated automatically. This property can be used in other script actions, for instance to create an Exchange mailbox and setup group memberships.

Base.Explanation: Set the value of an attribute of an Active Directory object, for instance a user account. The attribute is specified by the LDAP display name of the attribute. For the most common properties, the LDAP name can be selected from a list.

ArrayElement.Name: User Object
ArrayElement.Description: A data structure representing a user account. If you want to set the property of a user account object, you can use this property to specify the Active Directory object for this action. Use the action 'Get user (AD)' to find the user account in Active Directory and setup the variable that contains the 'User Object'.

ArrayElement.Name: Active Directory Object
ArrayElement.Description: A data structure representing a Active Directory object for which an attribute must be set. This property can only be used as a input variable. Earlier in the script, another script action must have generated the value for this variable.

ArrayElement.Name: Active Directory object LDAP name
ArrayElement.Description: The full LDAP name of the target Active Directory object. This object can be any object that exists in Active Directory: users, groups, OU's. The name must start with the Active Directory provider and optionally the binding information. Examples: LDAP://server_a/cn=GroupA,dc=TOOLS4EVER,dc=com, GC://cn=User1,DC=domain,DC=com.

ArrayElement.Name: LDAP attribute display name
ArrayElement.Description: The LDAP name of the attribute. The name identifies the attribute of the Active Directory object. For a number of well-known attributes, the LDAP name can be selected from a list but you can specify any other valid name.

ArrayElement.Name: Attribute value
ArrayElement.Description: The value of the attribute. The value must tbe specified as a text value.

ArrayElement.Name: Skip if new value empty
ArrayElement.Description: Default value: 'No'. Specify 'Yes' to ignore this action if the new attribute value is empty. In this case, the attribute is not changed. If this property is not specified or set to 'No', the target attribute is always updated.

ArrayElement.Name: Multi-value flag
ArrayElement.Description: Default value: 'No'. The value contains multiple entries (multi-value).

ArrayElement.Name: Append versus update multi-value flag
ArrayElement.Description: Default value: 'No'. When updating a multi-value attribute, the specified values can be appended to the the current values (property set to 'Yes') or the specified values can replace the current values (default, property set to 'No').
